For $x \ge 1,$ let $f$ be the function defined as follows:
\[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
\lfloor x \rfloor \left| x - \lfloor x \rfloor - \dfrac{1}{2 \lfloor x \rfloor} \right| & \text{if $x < \lfloor x \rfloor + \dfrac{1}{\lfloor x \rfloor}$}, \\
f \left( x - \dfrac{1}{\lfloor x \rfloor} \right) & \text{otherwise}.
\end{array}
\right.\]Let $g(x) = 2^{x - 2007}.$ Compute the number of points in which the graphs of $f$ and $g$ intersect. ||| Let \( n \) be an integer, and note that for each interval \( [n, n+1) \), we have the boundaries defined by \( n \) and \( n + \frac{1}{n} \). In this case, the function \( f(x) \) is linear from \( n \) to \( n + \frac{1}{n} \), giving us exactly one intersection with the graph of \( g(x) = 2^x \) in each interval for a total of 2006 intervals. Consequently, the total number of intersection points is only 2006, resulting in \( \boxed{2006} \).

