The horizontal asymptote is $y = -1,$ and the only vertical asymptote is $x = 2.$  Find $\frac{p(-1)}{q(-1)}.$ ||| Given the vertical asymptote at $x = 2$, I will assume $q(x) = (x - 2)^3$ instead of a square. The numerator must have roots at $x = 4$ and $x = -5$, so I’ll let $p(x) = k(x - 4)(x + 5)$. The function is then \[y = \frac{k(x - 4)(x + 5)}{(x - 2)^3}.\] The horizontal asymptote being $y = -1$ suggests $k = -1$, leading to \[y = -\frac{(x - 4)(x + 5)}{(x - 2)^3}.\] Evaluating at $x = -1$, we get \[y(-1) = -\frac{(-5)(4)}{(-3)^3} = -\frac{-20}{-27} = \frac{20}{27}. \] Hence, \( \frac{p(-1)}{q(-1)} = \boxed{\frac{20}{27}}.\]

summary:
Circle $C_1$ has center $(10,0)$ and radius 6.  Let $A = (10,0).$  Circle $C_2$ has center $(-15,0)$ and radius 9.  Let $B = (-15,0).$

[asy]
unitsize(0.2 cm);

pair A, B, D, P, Q, R;

A = (10,0);
B = (-15,0);
D = (0,0);
P = intersectionpoint(Circle(A,6),arc((A + D)/2, abs(A - D)/2, 180, 360));
Q = intersectionpoint(Circle(B,9),arc((B + D)/2, abs(B - D)/2, 0, 180));
R = extension(B,Q,A,A + P - Q);

draw(Circle(A,6));
draw(Circle(B,9));
draw(P--Q);
draw((-26,0)--(18,0));
draw(B--R--A);
draw(A--P);
draw(rightanglemark(B,Q,D,40));
draw(rightanglemark(A,P,D,40));
draw(rightanglemark(B,R,A,40));

dot("$A$", A, NE);
dot("$B$", B, S);
label("$D$", D, SW);
dot("$P$", P, SW);
dot("$Q$", Q, N);
label("$R$", R, N);
[/asy]

The shortest such segment $\overline{PQ}$ will be an internal common tangent of the two cirlces, and $\angle BQD = \angle APD = 90^\circ.$  Extend $\overline{BQ}$ past $Q$ to $R$ so that $QR = PA.$  Then $APQR$ is a rectangle.

We have that $BR = BQ + QR = BQ + PA = 9 + 6 = 15$ and $AB = 25.$  Then by Pythagoras on right triangle $ARB,$
\[AR = \sqrt{AB^2 - BR^2} = \sqrt{25^2 - 15^2} = 20.\]Therefore, $PQ = AR = \boxed{20}.$

