Let $p(x)$ be a polynomial of degree 4 such that $p(55) = p(83) = p(204) = p(232) = 8$ and $p(103) = 13.$  Find
\[p(1) - p(2) + p(3) - p(4) + \dots + p(285) - p(286).\] ||| Let $q(x) = p(x) - 8$. Then, since $p(55) = p(83) = p(204) = p(232) = 8$, we have $q(55) = q(83) = q(204) = q(232) = 0$. Therefore, $q(x)$ has roots at these points and can be expressed as $q(x) = c(x - 55)(x - 83)(x - 204) + d$ for some constants $c$ and $d$. Hence, $p(x) = c(x - 55)(x - 83)(x - 204) + d + 8$. Since $p(287 - x) 
eq p(x)$, $p(1) - p(2) + p(3) - p(4) + 	ext{...} + p(285) - p(286) = 7. \boxed{7}

summary:
Since three of the roots of $p(x)$ are 1, 2, and 3, we can write
\[p(x) = (x - 1)(x - 2)(x - 3)(x - r).\]Then
\begin{align*}
p(0) + p(4) &= (-1)(-2)(-3)(-r) + (3)(2)(1)(4 - r) \\
&= 6r + 24 - 6r = \boxed{24}.
\end{align*}

